            <!-- Theory & explanation -->
            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>Single-slit diffraction: formulas and concepts</h2>
              <p>
                When monochromatic light of wavelength \( \lambda \) passes
                through a narrow slit of width \( a \), it spreads out and forms
                a diffraction pattern on a distant screen. The pattern consists
                of a bright central maximum and weaker side maxima separated by
                dark minima.
              </p>

              <h3>Condition for minima (dark fringes)</h3>
              <p>
                For a single slit, destructive interference across the slit
                produces dark fringes at angles \( \theta_m \) given by:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ a \sin\theta_m = m\lambda,\quad m = \pm 1, \pm 2, \pm 3,
                \dots \]
              </div>
              <p>
                Here \( m \) is the order of the minimum. The central maximum
                corresponds to \( m = 0 \) and has no minimum at \( \theta = 0
                \).
              </p>

              <h3>Approximate position on the screen</h3>
              <p>
                If the screen is at distance \( L \) from the slit and the
                angles are small (in radians), then
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ y \approx L \tan\theta \approx L\theta. \] \[ y_m \approx
                \frac{m\lambda L}{a} \]
              </div>
              <p>
                The spacing between adjacent minima is therefore approximately
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \Delta y \approx \frac{\lambda L}{a}. \]
              </div>

              <h3>Central maximum width</h3>
              <p>
                The central bright fringe lies between the first minima at \( m
                = \pm 1 \). Its full width on the screen is
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ w_{\text{central}} \approx 2\frac{\lambda L}{a}. \]
              </div>

              <h3>Intensity distribution</h3>
              <p>The normalized intensity pattern for a single slit is</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \frac{I(\theta)}{I_0} = \left( \frac{\sin\beta}{\beta}
                \right)^2, \quad \beta = \frac{\pi a}{\lambda}\sin\theta, \]
              </div>
              <p>
                where \( I_0 \) is the intensity at \( \theta = 0 \). The minima
                occur when \( \beta = m\pi \) (with \( m \neq 0 \)), reproducing
                the condition \( a\sin\theta_m = m\lambda \).
              </p>

              <h3>Effect of slit width and wavelength</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Narrower slit (smaller \( a \))</strong>: pattern
                  spreads out, minima move farther from the center.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Longer wavelength (larger \( \lambda \))</strong>:
                  also broadens the diffraction pattern.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Larger screen distance \( L \)</strong>: linearly
                  scales all fringe positions on the screen.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How to use the single-slit diffraction calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Enter the <strong>wavelength</strong> of the light and choose
                  its unit (nm, µm, or m).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Enter the <strong>slit width</strong> and unit (mm, µm, or m).
                </li>
                <li>Specify the <strong>screen distance</strong> \( L \).</li>
                <li>
                  Choose the <strong>order</strong> \( m \) of the fringe you
                  are interested in.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>“Compute pattern”</strong> to see angles,
                  positions, fringe spacing and the intensity curve.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Small-angle vs exact calculation</h3>
              <p>
                For small diffraction angles (typically \( |\theta| \lesssim
                10^\circ \)), you can safely use the small-angle approximation
                \( \sin\theta \approx \tan\theta \approx \theta \) (in radians).
                For larger angles, uncheck
                <strong>“Use small-angle approximation”</strong> to use the
                exact trigonometric relations.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-10">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
                Single-slit diffraction – FAQ
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is the condition for minima in single-slit diffraction?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The dark fringes (minima) occur when the path difference
                    across the slit leads to complete destructive interference:
                    \( a \sin\theta_m = m\lambda \), where \( m = \pm 1, \pm 2,
                    \pm 3, \dots \). There is no minimum at \( m = 0 \);
                    instead, that corresponds to the central maximum.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How do I find the width of the central maximum?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The central maximum extends from the first minimum on one
                    side to the first minimum on the other side. Using the
                    small-angle approximation, its full width on the screen is
                    \( w_{\text{central}} \approx 2\lambda L / a \).
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is the difference between single-slit diffraction and
                    double-slit interference?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Single-slit diffraction arises from the finite width of a
                    single aperture and produces a broad envelope with a strong
                    central maximum and weaker side lobes. Double-slit
                    interference arises from the path difference between two
                    separate slits and produces many narrow, equally spaced
                    fringes. In real experiments, the double-slit interference
                    fringes are modulated by the single-slit diffraction
                    envelope of each slit.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    When is the Fraunhofer (far-field) approximation valid?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The Fraunhofer regime applies when the screen is far enough
                    from the slit that the wavefronts are effectively planar
                    across the aperture. A common rule of thumb is \( L \gg a^2
                    / \lambda \). In this regime, the pattern depends only on
                    angle and the simple formulas used in this calculator apply.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
            </section>
